@DATABASE DIY Project guide
@NODE MAIN "DIY Project - Audio Mixer "

    DIY Project: Audio Mixer Part 1 - by @{" Paul Harvey " LINK Author} <paul@aio.co.uk>
 __________________________________________________________________________
 а
 I  started this little project a while back when I got a SCSI CDROM for my
 A1200 and got a bit annoyed when I couldn't hear the CD audio. I never got
 around to finishing it, as I ended up buying an A4000 anyway, which has an
 onboard  audio mixer.  This part will show you what's involved in building
 a `Summing' amp.

                          @{" Audio Mixer Part 1 " LINK Part_1}

 In  Part  One we looked at some ideas for building an audio mixer using an
 OP Amp IC.  In  Part 2 we look at building either an `Active' or `Passive'
 Audio Mixer.

                          @{" Audio Mixer Part 2 " LINK Part_2}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Part_1 "Audio Mixer Part 1..."

 If you have ever tried mixing audio signals by just hooking the two inputs
 in  parallel,  you  would have heard a great deal of noise, and decided it
 was  a  bad  idea.  A  better  way is to use an  OP Amp IC  to add the two
 signals together properly. The IC will cost you about $2 AUSD at the most.
 Together  with  a  few  discrete components, you can configure the IC as a
 `Summing Non-inverting' Operational Amplifier for less than $5 AUSD.

 What you will need:

 ░ 4x 10k ohm resistors
 ░ 2x 10uf electrolytic capacitors
 ░ 2x 100uf electrolytic capacitors
 ░ 4x 47k ohm variable trim pots/potentiometers
 ░ 2x Operational Amplifiers
      Get  a  `dual'  or  `quad'  IC  that has 2 or more in it, and is made
      specifically for Audio applications. Alternatively, use 2x741 general
      purpose  Op  Amps  (or it's 4 in one package equivalent, the LM324N),
      though the output may not have as good a quality. Alternative Op Amps
      and their @{"pinouts" LINK Pinouts} are listed at the end.

 ░ A  piece of 5x5cm prototype matrix PCB  (predrilled with copper pads) or
   veroboard. Alternatively you could etch your own PCB.

 To use OP Amps, you need a few special power supply requirements:

                        0v (ground), +9v and -9v.

 There  are  some  fancy tricks you can use to get -9 and +9v from a 0v/18v
 source, but I think the easiest way is to use the -12v and +12v lines that
 are  running  around  inside  your computer. The 741 can actually handle a
 potential difference of up to 36v; -12v and +12v should work fine for most
 OP Amps. Check the specifications of the chip you purchase, though.

 For Amiga 1200's in the keyboard case with external PSU...

 Square PSU Plug:

                        Pin No.   Description
                        -----------------------
                        а1ааааааа +5v DC
                        а2ааааааа Shield Ground
                        *3ааааааа +12v DC
                        *4ааааааа 0v/Ground
                        *5ааааааа -12v DC

 For Amigas towered in a case with an AT PSU...

 AT mainboard power connector plug:  (ie. not the Molex/FDD power plugs)

                 Pin No.   Description     Usual colour
                 --------------------------------------
                 а1.аааааа Power Good *ааааOrange
                 а2.аааааа +5VdcаааааааааааRed
                 *3.аааааа +12VdcааааааааааYellow
                 *4.аааааа -12VdcааааааааааBlue
                 *5.аааааа GroundааааааааааBlack
                 *6.аааааа GroundааааааааааBlack
                 *7.аааааа GroundааааааааааBlack
                 *8.аааааа GroundааааааааааBlack
                 а9.аааааа -5VdcаааааааааааWhite
                 10.аааааа +5VdcаааааааааааRed
                 11.аааааа +5VdcаааааааааааRed
                 12.аааааа +5VdcаааааааааааRed

 Items with an asterix next to them are the wires you will need.

 For wiring this, follow the @{" schematic " SYSTEM "sys:utilities/multiview MIXER_16.iff"}.

 Well,  that's all you need to know. As always, keep in mind that what I've
 suggested here could be incorrect. If you are serious about building this,
 please  double  check my PSU pinouts from another source, and double check
 your  own  connections  before  you  power anything up! I don't accept any
 responsibility  for  any of the information presented here; use it at your
 own risk. To the best of my knowledge, and to the best of my ability, I've
 tried  to  make  all  pinouts  and  information listed here as accurate as
 possible.  I've  put the circuit through a software simulator, and nothing
 blew up... :)

 In Part Two I'll report how my own summing amp goes, ie. whether the whole
 idea is flawed or not ;) If you make this yourself, tell us about it!

@ENDNODE
@NODE Part_2 ""Audio Mixer Part 2..."

    DIY Project: Audio Mixer Part 2 - by @{" Paul Harvey " LINK Author} <paul@aio.co.uk>
 __________________________________________________________________________

 The `Active Audio Mixer'...

 In Part One we looked at some ideas  for  building an audio mixer using an
 OP  Amp  IC.  The good news is, I got one built, and it works fine. I used
 the  LM324  general  purpose quad input OP Amp IC, which means it is an IC
 package  containing  four  general  purpose  OP  Amps. Using the schematic
 presented in Part One,  with a few slight modifications, the unit was very
 effective.  It  successfully mixes two audio inputs, and boosts the output
 signal quite significantly.

 The  only  main  concern  with using a computer PSU is that the computer's
 hardware, such as hard disks, put varying loads on the power supply, which
 could cause noise in our amplifier. To combat this, the original schematic
 had  a  large  470uf  capacitor  to  try and smooth things out, across the
 -12v/+12v  supply. I didn't like this idea, so I used two 470uF capacitors
 instead  -  one the went across the 0v and +12v rail, and the other across
 0v and -12v.

 Even  with  these  capacitors removed, there was no detectable noise, even
 with  two hard disks copying data form one to the other. Also, the general
 purpose OP Amp produced audio that was indistinguishable from the original
 sources.  Well, using my hi-fi setup, that is.

 I've  recompiled  a  parts  list  for  the  final schematic. The only real
 changes  are  an extra 470uF capacitor, and only two 47k trim pots are now
 needed,  instead of two for each channel. This time, the two inputs should
 tap onto the outer legs of the trimpot, whilst the middle one should go to
 the  input  on  the  OP  Amp.  If you have good quality trim pots (if such
 things  exist),  and you don't want one input to have bias over the other,
 just  adjust  the  trim pots so that they are turned to the center. If you
 must  give  one input bias over the other, keep in mind you can't turn the
 pot  all  the  way anti-clockwise or clockwise, as this may produce noisey
 output.  Make  sure  there is at least 10k ohms between each input and the
 capacitor on the input of the OP Amp.

 What you will need:

 ░ 4x 10k ohm resistors
 ░ 2x 10uF electrolytic capacitors
 ░ 2x 100uF electrolytic capacitors
 ░ 2x 470uF electrolytic capacitors
 ░ 2x 47k ohm variable trim pots/potentiometers
 ░ 4x RCA sockets (2x for Amiga -> mixer, 2x for mixer -> amp)
 ░ Stereo RCA cable (mixer -> amp hookup)
 ░ 1x Socket suitable for your CD ROM's audio output
 ░ 2x Operational Amplifiers
      Get  a  'dual'  or  'quad'  IC  that has 2 or more in it, and is made
      specifically for Audio applications. Alternatively, use 2x741 general
      purpose  OP  Amps  (or it's 4 in one package equivalent, the LM324N),
      though the output may not have as good a quality. Alternative OP Amps
      and their @{"pinouts" LINK Pinouts} are listed at the end.

 ░ A  piece of 5x5cm prototype matrix PCB  (predrilled with copper pads) or
   veroboard. Alternatively you could etch your own PCB.

 ░ 1x Zippy box or similar to house it all.
   Optionally, if you're daring and don't mind smoke, you can just leave it
   dangle there.

 Here is the final @{" schematic " SYSTEM "sys:utilities/multiview ActiveMIXER.iff"}.

 After you have soldered in all the discrete components and got the circuit
 all  hooked  up, now you have to add the two RCA jacks for input from your
 Amiga,  the  two RCA jacks for output to your existing amp, and the socket
 for  your  CD ROM audio. For power, the neat and professional way to do it
 would  be  to  make  up  a  passthrough connector from the power plugs and
 sockets  out of an old motherboard and powersupply, but chances are you've
 already  bodged  that  up  anyway,  seeing  your  A1200  doesn't need such
 connectors.

 The `Passive Audio Mixer'...

 If  you are the lazy type, and find IC's scary,  there is a simpler way to
 mix your audio. This is a cheap and nasty way of doing things, compared to
 our  active  mixer  I've  just described, but it works. It's really just a
 couple of variable resistors thrown together, but some people like to call
 it   a   `Passive'   audio   mixer.   It's  passive  because  there  isn't
 any amplification and the result is an output that's mixed OK, but weaker.
 (hence the need for amplification)

 If you take a close look at the schematic for the `Active' mixer, you will
 see  that  before the two input signals for each channel go anywhere, they
 are  joined  together  with  a  variable  resistor. All the OP Amp does is
 boosts  the  output  signal.  The actual `mixing' is done by the resistor.
 This  pre-amplification is ideal for a professional situation,  because if
 it  wasn't  boosted  here,  your  main amp would be turned up a great deal
 more.  If  you've got cheap equipment, this might mean you have a constant
 background hiss, but it is something to avoid.

 So I'll give you the info you need to build a `passive' mixer. It's really
 quite simple. а

 What you will need:

 ░ 2x 47k ohm variable trim pots/potentiometers
 ░ Some prototype matrix PCB (predrilled with copper pads) or veroboard, OR
   just solder the beggars on the spot with some hookup wire.
 ░ 4x RCA sockets (2x for Amiga -> mixer, 2x for mixer -> amp)
 ░ Stereo RCA cable (mixer -> amp hookup)
 ░ 1x Socket suitable for your CD ROM's audio output
 ░ 1x Zippy box or similar to house it all.
   Optionally, if you're daring and don't mind smoke, you can just leave it
   dangle there.а

 Here is the @{" schematic " SYSTEM "sys:utilities/multiview PassiveMIXER.iff"}.

 So, now you don't have any excuse to not to use your A1200 as a CD player.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Pinouts "OP Amp pinouts..."

 Pinouts of...

 the  LM324  (General  Purpose Quad Operational Amplifier IC) and the LF347
 (JFET Low Noise Quad Operational Amplifier IC)

                        Pin No.   Description
                        ---------------------
                        а1ааааааа Out 1
                        а2ааааааа In 1 -
                        а3ааааааа In 1 +
                        а4ааааааа +ve
                        а5ааааааа In 2 +
                        а6ааааааа In 2 -
                        а7ааааааа Out 2
                        а8ааааааа Out 3
                        а9ааааааа In 3 -
                        10ааааааа In 3 +
                        11ааааааа -ve
                        12ааааааа In 4 +
                        13ааааааа In 4 -
                        14ааааааа Out 1

 Pinouts of...

 the  LF353  (JFET  Low  Noise Dual Operational Amplifier IC) and the LM833
 (HiFi Dual Operational Amplifier IC)

                        Pin No.   Description
                        ---------------------
                        а1ааааааа Out 1
                        а2ааааааа In 1 -
                        а3ааааааа In 1 +
                        а4ааааааа -ve
                        а5ааааааа In 2 +
                        а6ааааааа In 2 -
                        а7ааааааа Out 2
                        а8ааааааа +ve

@ENDNODE
